segments.text: Okay, this is January 8th, 1981, and Eric and I are, me as Bob Cornish, we are in the office of Kevin Stowers at St. Edward's University in Austin, Texas.
Kevin is in charge of environmental studies at St. Edward's, and he has been in Austin for two and a half years, subsequent to having taught at Utah State.

for five years and before that he was the assistant planning director in Galveston which brings us to the point of this interview we would like to ask you Kevin to give us the benefit of your understanding and knowledge about Galveston first and secondly would you like to just take a look at these questions we've provided for you

One thing that I think that I need to say about Galveston particularly that a lot of people don't realize is that the historical records of Galveston and particularly municipal records in many cases are very poor and this is because every time there's a major hurricane, a number of records are lost.
The records are damaged.
The historical tradition in Galveston has been records are damaged.
They're simply carted out and hauled away rather than trying to be preserved.
This includes city council minutes, ordinances, whatever.
And of course, after each disaster, there is a massive renovation and major changes are made.
So... Can we stop one minute?
Sure.
Of course, all of you know historically after the 1900 hurricane, which was a massive disaster that leveled the town completely.
There were almost no buildings left standing.
They were undamaged.

uh the outcome of that was they founded a commission form of government which is one of those rather strange little devices that you kind of learn about that continued on for some time we're going to be busy for a while okay and um the outcome
of that is that they continued under a commission form of government for quite some period of time.
I don't know when officially they moved from that commission form of government, but in 1961 a new civic charter was adopted which set up a city manager form of government.
That is what I would consider to be the time of new modern planning, new modern administration in the city of Galveston.
The 61 Charter was also a response to a disaster.
They had a hurricane in 61.
And so, you know, what do we do?
We have an opportunity for a major change.
There would have been the usual problems with the commission form of government.
And at that stage in 61,
They established a whole series of citizen commissions, among which was the Planning Commission, a Traffic Commission, a Transportation Commission, and so forth and so on.
This apparently became the backbone and basis for modern planning efforts in the city of Galveston.
And I really cannot speak very well for what happened prior to that, because again, the records were thrown out in 61.
They got wet, and a lot of them just simply got carried off.
Also, there's a tremendous storage problem.
City Hall is an older one, and they run out of space.
And it seems like with a lot of communities, nobody holds these old records.
You can't give them away.
And so if you're left with the prospect of continuing your municipal operations,
are ceasing them to become an archive, most communities quite naturally find a dumpster somewhere and get rid of these things.
And it helps when you get them wet and they're damaged and they're going to deteriorate anyway.
That just spurs the movement on.
So Galveston, I think, is going to be a difficult community to study in that sense.
The first modern plan, which I managed to figure out, is a Marvin Springer.
document, or the one that they were operating under when I was there in 1973, comprehensive plan in Port City of Galveston.
I don't know what they had prior to that.

I somewhat have a feeling, especially by what I saw sitting in the planning offices in the storage room for the drafting department, they were tending to operate off a poster board and had never really, you know, gone through a unified document procedure up until that point.

and these things take time, so I don't know that 12 years later seems like a long time to students, but on the other hand, in reality, getting a plan adopted 12 years after you initiate the process and procedures, that's not too bad.
I don't have the zoning ordinance.
I loaned it to a colleague who hasn't returned it, and

If I recall correctly, the zoning ordinance was adopted in either 64 or 67 that they're operating under, which was probably prior to the Marvin Spranger plant, but it may have well been based upon documents that had been adopted in a more casual attitude and atmosphere for this plant.
Is there any periodic review of the Springer plan?
Well, when I was there, yes.
Now, of course, there's a distinction between what a periodic review in terms of citizen input hearings, you know, a formal readoption by the city council, and what the staffs do.
I think inevitably the staffs are always reviewing
and updating these documents.
There's nothing else simply to keep their engineering data, their population data, their housing data up to date.
Furthermore, it's almost required that the data be updated simply in terms of grant applications.
And this was something we were pursuing very hard when I was in Galveston.
We took the city from
If I remember my figures right, I had one year from $150,000 in federal grants to something like $1.4 million.
When you do that, that involves massive inputs in terms of document review and updating.
The systematic review of the document, when I was there, it was a very modern document.
It was only a year or two old.
And so therefore, we had not gone through a five year review.

It's my understanding that the document is probably, from what I've judged just reading and talking to a couple people, has been reviewed in a very serious way in the last year or two, but I would have to check with my people in Galveston to find that out for sure.
What administrative procedures and planning program elements does Galveston have for implementing community plans?
At the present, I don't know.
They've got a planning department, I know that.
What about the manager's role?
I mean, that seems to have... Well, Galveston's been hard on managers.
As a matter of fact, good managers frequently find other things to do in Galveston within two or three years.
Most managers do not last very long in Galveston because they're either competent and good and move on to better things that are offered to them or else they're fired.
Why does this happen, Kevin, would you say?
I mean, clearly the council's fault here.
Oh, well, the council is certainly a representative of the community and it represents that cross-section in a very interesting manner.
If you look at Galveston, it's probably one of the most diverse communities in the state of Texas.
As a matter of fact, when they looked at segregation patterns, Galveston was listed as being one of the most integrated cities in the United States in the early 1960s.
Well, in reality, those people are not dealing with each other in terms of social aspect.

It's just such an old city that's so compact and so many uses of land mixed together that you can have part of a block being black, part of it being white, and part being Spanish-American without those people ever really interacting and to say hello and nice to see you.
And this is one of the essential characters of Galveston.
It's a very compact, small island.
Also, there's a tremendous amount of wealth in Galveston.
Historically, it was the premier city in the state of Texas until the 1900 storm, and there's tremendous wealth there today.
There is also perhaps some of the most acute poverty problems that you will ever see.
When I was there, the median education level for adults over the age of 25, if I remember my statistics correctly, was eighth grade.
But it's got the University of Texas Medical Branch there.
It's got a junior college.
They've got a lot of major corporations and headquarters there, financial institutions.
Yet, you know, here you have a very poorly educated and functioning- You don't want to forget Texas A&M's campus.
Oh, no.
I'm sorry.
I keep forgetting about them.
It's hard to forget them.
They keep changing their mind what kind of sign they want.
As a result, the traffic people told them where they could go with their sign and that sign was not going to be changed again as long as there was a city of Galveston.
They had a name change recently, you know.
Yeah, well this was actually before that.

They kept trying to decide, you know, they wanted to be capitals in which part of the school they wanted to emphasize and, you know, what should come first and on the side and, you know, so it got to be the point it was kind of ridiculous.
We keep trying to get changes every six months to a year.
It gets expensive.
That doesn't sound difficult, does it?
No, no.
Things have changed.
But Galveston is a very diverse community, and there's a lot of conflicts.
Also, it's got a tremendously sensitive environment.

Before we leave this point, though, I think it's particularly critical of Galveston, from my understanding, because they've gone through umpteen city managers and planning directors and planning staffs, and I think that we ought to
The gentleman that was there prior to my venue, which would be the late 60s, early 70s, tried to undertake an urban renewal program.
I don't remember the guy's name.
He went to Mississippi.
There's a great movement along the coast, the southern coast of planter directors that are moving to other similar communities from their previous occupation.
Like Bruce.
Yes.
And the outcome was that
There was a lot of animosity created because Galveston being a compact city, there's no way you can really do anything without tearing something down.
And of course everybody knows what's going to be torn down and there was a lot of
real conservative feeling politically in this period.
He was not successful in the referendum and getting the urban renewal projects, programs pushed through and accepted by the community.
He got little things like one-way airplane tickets back to his home on the east coast in the mail, which he promptly cashed in and threw a party with for the staff.
Somebody mailed that?
Oh yes, anonymously.
So there was a good feeling of animosity.
At that point, there was a lot of reorganization.
There was a feeling that Galveston was not getting its due, that things needed to be done.
And certain progressive elements in the community, and you can call them progressive or renegade or radical, depending on what your view is, happened to me.
Well, the Moody Foundation, interestingly enough, does like to see certain things done and is a very powerful force in Galveston.
Mrs. Northern is quite a force.
If you want to know which religion to undertake, just see where she puts her money and go accordingly.
They may be interested in funding the continuation of this project.
Yeah.
Well, that's good.
They are interested in those types of things.
That's the kind of project they would fund.
They would fund libraries, cultural centers, historical renovation, things of this nature.
It's very positive educational ventures, religious ventures.
They are a powerful force within Galveston, and particularly
But beyond that, there was a lot of feeling that Galveston was not going anywhere.
It was being passed by.

It hadn't grown between 50 and 60, and the hurricane had whopped it, and the 1970 census came out, and it lost a little bit of population, and there was a lot of concern about where Galveston was going to be in the future.
There's this old syndrome that if you're not growing, there's something somehow unhealthy about you as a community.
And you have a lot of business interests in the community.
Excuse me.
The house.
Shook hands with all of you before I told you.
Oh, a little bit of illness in the house, so I shook hands with all of you before I mentioned it.
Eric looks happy.
But, oh, just a stomach bug, cramps.
Probably the flu.
Yes, something.
I'm not sure what the symptoms of that.
But Galveston has this real concern over where it's going in the future, and it didn't seem to be going much of anywhere.
It seemed to be the same old place.
There was not a lot of new investment, a lot of people moving in, and it was very difficult to get things done.
At this stage, they hired a community development director, Dean Mayberry, spelled without a Y, M-A-B-E-R-R-Y.
out of Hartford, Connecticut, and he had been at Hartford and New Haven running their programs up there and had done some really dynamite things.

They had had a position open for some time and they just couldn't get anybody hired and they contacted him because he was very experienced in taking older cities that seemed to be kind of stabilizing and stagnating and turning things around and getting things happening.

uh he came in and they took the city traffic engineer and made him planning director and consolidated planning and traffic engineering transportation which in some ways actually makes some sense although I wouldn't I would have chosen myself to be director but I wasn't there at the time
But it does make some sense, and they put planning and traffic under the Community Development Department.
They gave them systematic and concentrated code enforcement, which are two federal programs that have been undergoing, and were very unsuccessful at getting much done.

You know, it seemed like you get a loan application and it sits there three years later, you know, or every year they process four or five, you know, instead of the 75 or 80 that they should be shoving through.
They gave them building inspection under that program as well.
I came in about that stage as an intern, by the way, out of A&M.
They offered me, after I completed my internship, a position as assistant director of planning.
We had a Harvard planning grad who was a specialist in housing.
Working for me, an architecture student major out of A&M who was working as a planner.
Usual sort of miscellaneous staff.
We had a public administration specialist working in the department.
So I and the Harvard were the two core identified design or unit planners, which is no big deal in and of itself.
We also had the usual secretarial staff, three or four people sitting in our office, plus a couple of people in drafting and graphics.
And things began to happen, and the decision, of course, was the dean was going to go after federal funding.
And we went after federal funding in a very serious way.
As a matter of fact, if I remember right, we were the second community in the Houston-Galliston area council to get, say, our transit system shoved through and approved by the council.
We went after Community Development Block Grants, which were just coming out at that time, in 1974.
We looked very seriously at EDA, LEAA, everything that had money attached to it.
We wanted to try to find some way to make use of it.
and things began to happen.

There were a lot of things, money coming in, a lot of things happening, and we had a very confident city manager at the time, whose face I remember for some reason right at the moment, his name slips me, and just as everything was beginning to look just fantastic about a year into the program,
And things were going along very well, and lots of money's pouring into the city, and lots of things are finally coming to fruition.
And we got an emergency medical system, you know, took it away from the funeral homes finally.
We still have funeral homes that run ambulances and college stationers.
We have, we have funeral home ambulances too.
They're now hospitals.
Very good.
The outcome of all of that was that the city manager got a rather fabby kind of offer from one of the accounting firms in town.
He thought about it and he took the position.
for a much higher salary, and he got to work 40 hours a week, and he got to go home and see his family in the evening, and there were no night meetings.
And it was just wonderful, and he's very happy about that.
And at that stage, a very interesting kind of thing happened.
Under the city charter in Galveston... Do you know what year that was?
Was that 62?
No, this is 74.
I mean 72.
Yeah.
Under the city charter in Galveston, if they can't make up their mind about what to do in terms of a city manager, the finance director becomes the acting city manager.
Why it wouldn't be one of the assistant city managers, I don't know, or whatever.
But the wisdom of the voters in 61 indicated the finance department was the logical direction and step to go.
Well, they couldn't make up their mind.
They had applicants from all over because it looked like things were finally turned around.
Good things were happening in Galveston.
Salary scale was quite reasonable in getting up there.
And the outcome
was that out of these 30 or 50 or 60 or 80 wonderful applications, two people on staff wanted it.
One was Dean Mayberry, director of community development.
The other was Jack Nicklaus or whatever his name was, not the golfer, but the director of finance.
And as the negotiations went on, and the city council hemmed and hawed and wouldn't make up their mind about what to do,
They turned around and let Nicholas take it as acting director.
Well, of course, if somebody's acting director for three or four months, and then they have to make a decision who is likely to get the position, acting director, if he hasn't screwed it up royally.
Nicholas played some real dirty politics and backstabbing, spread a lot of rumors, you know, usual dirty municipal infighting.
I don't know anything about that.
You don't know anything about that?
Coming from university.
Yes, and that never happens in universities, does it?
No, especially Catholic universities.
No.
And the outcome is that

Nicholas was appointed, Mayberry did not get to nod, and it was obvious that because of the nature of the fight that had occurred in the campaign for the position, that Mayberry was going to, although he was offered and everybody wanted to stay on, everybody said wonderful things about him, that, you know, he was not in a position particularly to stay on.
So, you know, he dropped, let the ball drop, and within a week he had a position for more money elsewhere, and he's working in Waco now with
with their mental health, mental retardation unit, the last I heard.

Now that was a unit that had a scandal, and he went in and ended up, I don't know if you remember back in the mid-70s, it was a scandal, and giving funny injections to patients, and not keeping records on drugs, and oh yes, wonderful, typical good Texas stuff.
And so anyway, he got brought in to clean that act up, and he had worked in Waco previously, so he was kind of going home to him.
Nicholas, yeah, I was aware of that.
He was among those that kind of got it started way back in the 60s in working community development.
Anyway, Nicholas took an interesting style of management.
Basically, the clothing style in the city manager's office became leisure suits.
with jump boots that were bloused.
Jump boots?
Jump boots.
Military jump boots.
Carrying police shortwave radios on their hips so they could race to any emergency in town.
Yeah.
I took one look at that and I said, yeah, this is weird.
Now Jack had been a Marine back in Corita.
He had been a college football player and had been a pro lineman for a year or two back in the early 50s with the Baltimore Colts.
And when he started wearing leisure suits that were bloused with junk boots and police band or short-wave radios, I kind of looked at that and I said, this is a little strange.
Furthermore, I am sick and tired of educating city managers.
Every time we get a program up and going, the city manager comes in and we educate him and get his support and things go along real nicely and smoothly.
And then he quits and goes elsewhere.

Well, I finally thought about it for a while, and I was really disgusted because I'd gotten three or four things I'd been working real hard on that had been busted partly as part of the disruption from the transition.
And I got a phone call one day saying, hi, this is Carlisle Becker at Utah State calling, and we hear that you might be interested in teaching the university.
And I said, sure.
Fly me up, talk to me, and make me a money offer.
And they did.
And I did.
I went.
I quit.
Most of the planners on staff quit.
One planner got sucked in, Danny Fred, who was the housing man, downstairs at the city manager's office.
I'm not sure what his job ultimately became, but he worked downstairs for a year, year and a half, making very good money.
And Jack managed to show his political acumen by running a budget deficit of something like a half million dollars.
One year.
Now, in a community the size of Galveston, a half million dollars does attract attention.
And he got canned, strangely enough.
And Danny, who I got this information from, says, well...
being single and from a wealthy family, it's time that I take a year or two and recuperate from all of this rather hard work and frayed nerves and so forth.
And so he resigned and he lived in, pardon me, Danny Fred, one of the other planners that go down to the city manager's office.
He resigned, went out to San Francisco and lived out there for a year or two before he got another job, you know, just living off his savings.
And then he got a job somewhere in the Midwest, I think in Ohio, I don't know.

And so at that stage, I lost contact with Galveston other than I hear Bruce says there's never been any planning done in Galveston, which is nice because if you look at the original city plan, be it engineering, civil engineering or not, you'll see that they've got an old map in here showing the original city as it was laid out by our friendly survey.
Yeah.
So, you know, it certainly was a planned community in every sense of the world in 1836 when it became a city.
And I think the level of planning that's occurred there, you know, certainly rigid subdivisions, the seagull, you can see very definite strong engineering and planning type responses.
Now certainly that's not modern planning in any sense of the word, but on the other hand,

you know there's been a lot of things done and it reflects and i think it shows in the community it's kind of a strange community in a lot of ways but you know there it is so that's where we've been with the city for some time and i don't know what they've done since then they do have some physical and environmental problems that are just absolutely phenomenal
that may wind up finally crippling the city in a total sense.
My feeling in the time I was there was the city had no business being there.
I never said that when I was there.
That was an unacceptable position.
But the entire city is basically in a flood plain except for the area right on top of the seawall.
The flood frequency from hurricanes is one hurricane hits there once every 10 years.
The entire city basically goes under water.
The area is subject to subsidence from the Houston-Galveston region.
It relies on underground water from out to Loma Wells on the mainland, and it pumps water over to the island.

And it's suffering a very serious coastal erosion problem, which was observable, and it was a problem when I was there that apparently has accelerated to as much as 25 feet per year on parts of the island.
So, and when you consider the island at Twyatt Point is about two miles, two and a half miles across, you've got some very interesting things happening.
In terms of my long-term view, I would not live on Galveston Island.
I might, if I was wealthy, I might buy a house behind the seawall if I could find one that was available.
It's probably not the kind of community you want to be looking at in terms of long-term investments.
Now, there's a lot of money there and a lot of ways to make money, so people will go there and they'll live there.
It's got a lot of very desirable things about it, climate, beach, water recreation.
And this is the real problem with the Texas coast.
Those islands happen to be where you can get to the beach.
That's where your recreational potential is.
South Padre Island's got exactly the same problem, except that it hasn't been there for 150, 175 years.
There's no record of who did the first plat on the coast.
Is there?
Who's responsible for the design?
Because there is some design in this.
Oh, yes.
Yeah, there are some books on the history of Galveston that are available in the library.
I don't recall the guy's name now that laid out the city.
But yeah, certainly it is a very definitely designed city.
And you can look at it very thoroughly.
There are some features in it that remind me of Savannah.
Yeah.
Well, you've got a major boulevard coming into town.
You have basically a major drive along the beach.

open spaces yeah you've got regularly spaced open spaces some of which do not exist anymore you've got parks that are included you have essentially the urban area that's developed smaller city blocks the outlined areas that were viewed as being truck farm areas since then there have been roads cut these have become like avenue p and a half
their only numeric letter system grid system a very strong physical engineering sense of design very good
